{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_016cz3BqNWjJbfmZZrkSekyA","type":"tool_result","content":"# Revati's Runtime Prediction Approach\n\nRevati employs a **pluggable prediction interface** that supports both analytical and profiling-based methods. According to the paper:\n\n> \"Revati provides a pluggable interface supporting both analytical and profiling-based runtime predictors.\"\n\n## Specific Implementation\n\nBy default, the system extends existing analytical models from Vidur, enhancing them with support for modern features:\n\n> \"By default, we extend Vidur's operator-level models with support for Mixture-of-Experts routing, fused attention variants, and optimized all-reduce collectives.\"\n\n## Input Parameters\n\nThe predictor accounts for batch composition characteristics:\n\n> \"The predictor accepts batch composition (prefill count, decode count, sequence lengths) and target hardware spec, returning an estimated duration.\"\n\nThis design allows the system to model how different mixes of prefill and decode operations affect execution time.\n\n## Reported Accuracy\n\nRevati demonstrates strong prediction fidelity:\n\n> \"Revati achieves <<5% prediction error across multiple models and parallelism configurations, while running 5-17×faster than real GPU execution.\"\n\nThe sub-5% accuracy is maintained across varying model sizes, serving frameworks (vLLM and SGLang), and different workload characteristics, indicating the approach generalizes well without requiring framework-specific customization."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"57ed6f83-ecc3-4f10-b3c6-fefd71b307dd","tool_use_result":{"bytes":235711,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Revati's Runtime Prediction Approach\n\nRevati employs a **pluggable prediction interface** that supports both analytical and profiling-based methods. According to the paper:\n\n> \"Revati provides a pluggable interface supporting both analytical and profiling-based runtime predictors.\"\n\n## Specific Implementation\n\nBy default, the system extends existing analytical models from Vidur, enhancing them with support for modern features:\n\n> \"By default, we extend Vidur's operator-level models with support for Mixture-of-Experts routing, fused attention variants, and optimized all-reduce collectives.\"\n\n## Input Parameters\n\nThe predictor accounts for batch composition characteristics:\n\n> \"The predictor accepts batch composition (prefill count, decode count, sequence lengths) and target hardware spec, returning an estimated duration.\"\n\nThis design allows the system to model how different mixes of prefill and decode operations affect execution time.\n\n## Reported Accuracy\n\nRevati demonstrates strong prediction fidelity:\n\n> \"Revati achieves <<5% prediction error across multiple models and parallelism configurations, while running 5-17×faster than real GPU execution.\"\n\nThe sub-5% accuracy is maintained across varying model sizes, serving frameworks (vLLM and SGLang), and different workload characteristics, indicating the approach generalizes well without requiring framework-specific customization.","durationMs":4618,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.00397v1"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Xw2fZRJhCnhWTfu3YHuvvr","type":"tool_result","content":"# Frontier's Execution Time Modeling Approach\n\n## Overall Strategy\nFrontier uses an **Execution Predictor** component that decomposes logical layers into \"data-dependent micro-workflows of events\" rather than treating operators as monolithic units.\n\n## Features and Methods\n\n**Operator-specific modeling:**\n- **Attention**: Uses machine learning (random forest) trained on rich features including \"aggregate and distributional statistics of sequence lengths\" to capture workload dynamics under high input variance\n- **GroupedGEMM (MoE)**: Extracts features reflecting \"input properties and expert load distribution, such as token counts, expert number, model dimensions, expert selection ratios, and various load balance metrics\"\n\nBoth use **fine-grained profiling combined with regression models** rather than pure analytical approaches.\n\n## Prefill vs. Decode Handling\n\nFrontier models these as distinct stages in disaggregated systems with producer-consumer dynamics. The prefill stage generates KV-Caches; the decode stage consumes them with system-level backpressure coordination through the GlobalController.\n\n## MoE-Specific Handling\n\nThe system explicitly models straggler effects by:\n1. Simulating gating decisions to generate token-to-expert assignments\n2. Querying the GroupedGEMM model with actual token counts per expert\n3. Calculating latency as \"max[T_expert1, T_expert2, …, T_expertN]\" to capture synchronization barriers\n\n## Achieved Accuracy\n\n- **Attention operator**: 94%+ cases within 10% relative error\n- **GroupedGEMM**: 95%+ cases within 6% relative error\n- **End-to-end PD system**: 19.0–23.2% relative error across batch configurations"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"faa89c5c-04ec-49a1-b76b-427caf7e103d","tool_use_result":{"bytes":68276,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Frontier's Execution Time Modeling Approach\n\n## Overall Strategy\nFrontier uses an **Execution Predictor** component that decomposes logical layers into \"data-dependent micro-workflows of events\" rather than treating operators as monolithic units.\n\n## Features and Methods\n\n**Operator-specific modeling:**\n- **Attention**: Uses machine learning (random forest) trained on rich features including \"aggregate and distributional statistics of sequence lengths\" to capture workload dynamics under high input variance\n- **GroupedGEMM (MoE)**: Extracts features reflecting \"input properties and expert load distribution, such as token counts, expert number, model dimensions, expert selection ratios, and various load balance metrics\"\n\nBoth use **fine-grained profiling combined with regression models** rather than pure analytical approaches.\n\n## Prefill vs. Decode Handling\n\nFrontier models these as distinct stages in disaggregated systems with producer-consumer dynamics. The prefill stage generates KV-Caches; the decode stage consumes them with system-level backpressure coordination through the GlobalController.\n\n## MoE-Specific Handling\n\nThe system explicitly models straggler effects by:\n1. Simulating gating decisions to generate token-to-expert assignments\n2. Querying the GroupedGEMM model with actual token counts per expert\n3. Calculating latency as \"max[T_expert1, T_expert2, …, T_expertN]\" to capture synchronization barriers\n\n## Achieved Accuracy\n\n- **Attention operator**: 94%+ cases within 10% relative error\n- **GroupedGEMM**: 95%+ cases within 6% relative error\n- **End-to-end PD system**: 19.0–23.2% relative error across batch configurations","durationMs":6463,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.03148v1"}}
