{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01QJqdyaRqHxenQApwi2DzPg","type":"tool_result","content":"# FairBatching's Latency Prediction Model\n\n## Formula\n\nFairBatching uses a linear model to predict per-batch execution time:\n\n```\nbatch_time = a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context\n```\n\nWhere:\n- **a** = fixed overhead constant\n- **b** = coefficient for token processing cost\n- **c** = coefficient for KV cache access cost\n- **total_new_tokens** = number of new tokens in the batch\n- **total_context** = cumulative context length across all requests\n\n## Key Features\n\nThe model captures two primary computational costs:\n\n1. **Token Processing (FFN stage)**: Scales linearly with new tokens via coefficient `b`\n2. **KV Cache Access (Attention operators)**: Scales with total context length via coefficient `c`, since attention is \"memory-bandwidth bound\"\n\n## Accuracy\n\nThe authors report significant accuracy improvements:\n- **Strawman token-only approach**: ±5.2% error\n- **Final linear model**: ±1.3% error\n\n## Model Calibration\n\nParameters are \"built offline according to historical performance data and continuously calibrated to ensure accuracy.\" The system includes an automated testing framework (2,777 lines) that \"automatically profile[s] vLLM's runtime behavior, perform[s] linear regression, and determine[s] step-time modeling parameters for each model and GPU type.\"\n\nThis approach explicitly accounts for the GPU's memory-bandwidth limitations affecting attention operations, improving predictability compared to token-count-only budgets."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"0c204940-a19b-48d3-a925-f2082622b48c","tool_use_result":{"bytes":280546,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# FairBatching's Latency Prediction Model\n\n## Formula\n\nFairBatching uses a linear model to predict per-batch execution time:\n\n```\nbatch_time = a + b * total_new_tokens + c * total_context\n```\n\nWhere:\n- **a** = fixed overhead constant\n- **b** = coefficient for token processing cost\n- **c** = coefficient for KV cache access cost\n- **total_new_tokens** = number of new tokens in the batch\n- **total_context** = cumulative context length across all requests\n\n## Key Features\n\nThe model captures two primary computational costs:\n\n1. **Token Processing (FFN stage)**: Scales linearly with new tokens via coefficient `b`\n2. **KV Cache Access (Attention operators)**: Scales with total context length via coefficient `c`, since attention is \"memory-bandwidth bound\"\n\n## Accuracy\n\nThe authors report significant accuracy improvements:\n- **Strawman token-only approach**: ±5.2% error\n- **Final linear model**: ±1.3% error\n\n## Model Calibration\n\nParameters are \"built offline according to historical performance data and continuously calibrated to ensure accuracy.\" The system includes an automated testing framework (2,777 lines) that \"automatically profile[s] vLLM's runtime behavior, perform[s] linear regression, and determine[s] step-time modeling parameters for each model and GPU type.\"\n\nThis approach explicitly accounts for the GPU's memory-bandwidth limitations affecting attention operations, improving predictability compared to token-count-only budgets.","durationMs":5728,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.14392v1"}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_bdrk_01Kt3RrqdxUi9ydYaPLSMdXr","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-opus-4-6","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_bdrk_01SJ1k1Qag3jASdz6mEz8GMq","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2405.05465v1","prompt":"Extract the detailed methodology for how Vidur profiles and predicts per-step (per-iteration) execution time. What is the operator-level decomposition? How do they handle token-level vs sequence-level operators? What features do they use for regression/prediction? How do they combine individual operator predictions into overall step time? What accuracy do they report? Do they use separate models for prefill and decode?"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3067,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"31ec40b8-f3ac-4b8e-ba76-7d7b39c6dd6e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SJ1k1Qag3jASdz6mEz8GMq","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vidur's Execution Time Prediction Methodology\n\n## Operator-Level Decomposition\n\nVidur decomposes LLM operators into three categories based on input dependencies:\n\n1. **Token-level Operators**: Runtime depends only on total tokens processed (prefill + decode) in the batch. Includes matrix multiplications, activation functions, and normalization operations.\n\n2. **Sequence-level Operators**: Runtime depends on both current batch tokens and context length of each request. Primarily attention kernels.\n\n3. **Communication Operators**: Runtime depends solely on data transfer volume for all-reduce, all-gather, and send-recv operations.\n\n## Token-Level Operator Profiling\n\nThe system profiles all tensor parallel sharding configurations for matrix multiplications and point-wise operations. This enables simulating different parallelism strategies \"with minimal profiling performed on a single GPU.\"\n\n## Sequence-Level Operator Handling\n\n**Prefill Attention**: The team observes that prefill attention time is quadratic in sequence length. For a batch of P prefills with lengths p_i, they approximate runtime as equivalent to \"a single prefill of length √(Σp_i²).\"\n\n**Decode Attention**: Since decode operations are memory-bound, \"runtime is mainly determined by the total data volume...fetched from the KV-Cache\" rather than specific context length distributions.\n\n## Regression Approach\n\nRather than training MLPs (which require extensive data), Vidur employs \"random forest (RF) regression models\" to achieve \"balance between data frugality and fidelity.\"\n\n## Accuracy Reporting\n\n- Static workloads: Under 3.33% error on P95 latency across four models\n- Dynamic workloads at 85% capacity: Less than 5% error in most scenarios\n- Overall claim: \"under 9% error rate\" for request-level predictions\n\n## Integration into Step Time\n\nThe document does not explicitly detail how individual operator predictions combine into overall iteration time, though the hierarchical scheduler architecture suggests compositional assembly."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"e588bb4b-bf7a-41d0-a4fa-96db98015382","tool_use_result":{"bytes":169392,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Vidur's Execution Time Prediction Methodology\n\n## Operator-Level Decomposition\n\nVidur decomposes LLM operators into three categories based on input dependencies:\n\n1. **Token-level Operators**: Runtime depends only on total tokens processed (prefill + decode) in the batch. Includes matrix multiplications, activation functions, and normalization operations.\n\n2. **Sequence-level Operators**: Runtime depends on both current batch tokens and context length of each request. Primarily attention kernels.\n\n3. **Communication Operators**: Runtime depends solely on data transfer volume for all-reduce, all-gather, and send-recv operations.\n\n## Token-Level Operator Profiling\n\nThe system profiles all tensor parallel sharding configurations for matrix multiplications and point-wise operations. This enables simulating different parallelism strategies \"with minimal profiling performed on a single GPU.\"\n\n## Sequence-Level Operator Handling\n\n**Prefill Attention**: The team observes that prefill attention time is quadratic in sequence length. For a batch of P prefills with lengths p_i, they approximate runtime as equivalent to \"a single prefill of length √(Σp_i²).\"\n\n**Decode Attention**: Since decode operations are memory-bound, \"runtime is mainly determined by the total data volume...fetched from the KV-Cache\" rather than specific context length distributions.\n\n## Regression Approach\n\nRather than training MLPs (which require extensive data), Vidur employs \"random forest (RF) regression models\" to achieve \"balance between data frugality and fidelity.\"\n\n## Accuracy Reporting\n\n- Static workloads: Under 3.33% error on P95 latency across four models\n- Dynamic workloads at 85% capacity: Less than 5% error in most scenarios\n- Overall claim: \"under 9% error rate\" for request-level predictions\n\n## Integration into Step Time\n\nThe document does not explicitly detail how individual operator predictions combine into overall iteration time, though the hierarchical scheduler architecture suggests compositional assembly.","durationMs":6906,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2405.05465v1"}}
