{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ERnmd3XXnx37TM9NVEMHKP","type":"tool_result","content":"# AIConfigurator's Iteration-Level Latency Prediction Methodology\n\n## Core Approach\n\nAIConfigurator predicts per-step inference latency through **operator-level decomposition and profiling**. Rather than simulating entire inference runs, they break each iteration into fundamental computational primitives.\n\n## Operator-Level Profiling\n\nThe system decomposes inference iterations into repeated execution of key operators:\n\n- **GEMM operations** (parameterized by dimensions M,N,K and quantization levels)\n- **Attention mechanisms** (supporting MHA, GQA, MLA variants for both prefill and decode phases)\n- **Communication primitives** (AllReduce, AllGather, AllToAll, point-to-point transfers)\n- **MoE operations** (dispatch/combine patterns with expert routing)\n\nAs stated: *\"any inference iteration step can then be modeled as running a fixed sequence of operators for a number of times, typically depending on the number of layers\"*\n\n## Data Collection Strategy\n\nThey employ three complementary methods:\n\n1. **Exhaustive profiling** on actual GPU hardware (~30 GPU-hours per platform-framework pair)\n2. **Interpolation** for intermediate configurations using profiled data points\n3. **Speed-of-Light estimation** providing analytical roofline bounds for unmeasured operators\n\n## Aggregation Mechanism\n\nIteration latency is computed by **summing operator latencies**. The latency for each operator is queried from their calibrated performance database based on specific parameters (batch size, sequence length, dimensions). For models with multiple layers, operator latencies are multiplied by layer count.\n\n## Accuracy Achieved\n\nAcross diverse configurations:\n- **TPOT prediction**: 7.8% mean absolute percentage error overall\n- **Dense models** (Qwen3-32B): 8.2% MAPE\n- **MoE models** (Qwen3-235B): 6.8% MAPE\n- **Cross-framework** (vLLM): 11.9% MAPE\n\n## Handling Batch Composition\n\nThey model three distinct serving modes with different batch compositions:\n\n1. **Static mode**: Fixed batch size, sequential processing\n2. **Aggregated mode**: Mixed prefill/decode batches via continuous batching with rate-matching heuristics\n3. **Disaggregated mode**: Separate prefill and decode pools with independent optimization\n\nFor aggregated serving specifically, they use stride-based interpolation to reduce computational overhead: *\"interpolating costs over intervals rather than querying the database for every token step\"*"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa10f5df-2c8f-4bb1-b1a9-38b8d7356b7f","uuid":"5b3ce71b-616c-485c-8928-77ea8f38c13f","tool_use_result":{"bytes":250676,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# AIConfigurator's Iteration-Level Latency Prediction Methodology\n\n## Core Approach\n\nAIConfigurator predicts per-step inference latency through **operator-level decomposition and profiling**. Rather than simulating entire inference runs, they break each iteration into fundamental computational primitives.\n\n## Operator-Level Profiling\n\nThe system decomposes inference iterations into repeated execution of key operators:\n\n- **GEMM operations** (parameterized by dimensions M,N,K and quantization levels)\n- **Attention mechanisms** (supporting MHA, GQA, MLA variants for both prefill and decode phases)\n- **Communication primitives** (AllReduce, AllGather, AllToAll, point-to-point transfers)\n- **MoE operations** (dispatch/combine patterns with expert routing)\n\nAs stated: *\"any inference iteration step can then be modeled as running a fixed sequence of operators for a number of times, typically depending on the number of layers\"*\n\n## Data Collection Strategy\n\nThey employ three complementary methods:\n\n1. **Exhaustive profiling** on actual GPU hardware (~30 GPU-hours per platform-framework pair)\n2. **Interpolation** for intermediate configurations using profiled data points\n3. **Speed-of-Light estimation** providing analytical roofline bounds for unmeasured operators\n\n## Aggregation Mechanism\n\nIteration latency is computed by **summing operator latencies**. The latency for each operator is queried from their calibrated performance database based on specific parameters (batch size, sequence length, dimensions). For models with multiple layers, operator latencies are multiplied by layer count.\n\n## Accuracy Achieved\n\nAcross diverse configurations:\n- **TPOT prediction**: 7.8% mean absolute percentage error overall\n- **Dense models** (Qwen3-32B): 8.2% MAPE\n- **MoE models** (Qwen3-235B): 6.8% MAPE\n- **Cross-framework** (vLLM): 11.9% MAPE\n\n## Handling Batch Composition\n\nThey model three distinct serving modes with different batch compositions:\n\n1. **Static mode**: Fixed batch size, sequential processing\n2. **Aggregated mode**: Mixed prefill/decode batches via continuous batching with rate-matching heuristics\n3. **Disaggregated mode**: Separate prefill and decode pools with independent optimization\n\nFor aggregated serving specifically, they use stride-based interpolation to reduce computational overhead: *\"interpolating costs over intervals rather than querying the database for every token step\"*","durationMs":8685,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.06288v1"}}
